a%20back-up%20plan.%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EAs%20a%20child%2C%20there's%20no%20joy%20like%20opening%20a%20birthday%20card%20and%20seeing%20crisp%20dollar%20bills%20fall%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EGrowing%20up%2C%20my%20Dad%20tried%20to%20convince%20me%20that%20this%20cash%2C%20when%20saved%2C%20symbolized%20opportunity%20for%20my%20future%20self.%20I'd%20hold%20my%20birthday%20money%20up%20to%20the%20light%20to%20see%20the%20watermark%20and%20try%20to%20picture%20my%20future%20self%20enjoying%20this%20money%2C%20but%20all%20I%20could%20see%20was%20my%20current%20self%20enjoying%207%2F11%20Slurpees%2C%20top-ups%20for%20my%20pre-paid%20cellphone%2C%20and%20band%20tee%20shirts.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20I%20got%20my%20first%20job%20in%20high%20school%2C%20my%20Dad%20printed%20an%20article%20about%20the%20power%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fwhat-is-compound-interest%5C%22%3Ecompound%20interest%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20put%20it%20in%20my%20purse%20with%20a%20note%3A%20%26quot%3BStart%20investing%20early%2C%20Lizzie.%26quot%3B%20My%20money%20left%20my%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-checking-accounts%5C%22%3Echecking%20account%3C%2Fa%3E%20almost%20as%20soon%20as%20it%20entered%20that%20summer%2C%20and%20not%20because%20it%20was%20being%20funneled%20into%20a%20retirement%20account.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20after%20I%20graduated%20from%20college%20and%20got%20%26quot%3Bgrown-up%20jobs%2C%26quot%3B%20I%20didn't%20start%20saving.%20I%20contributed%20to%20my%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fwhat-is-401k%5C%22%3E401(k)%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20a%20while%2C%20only%20to%20empty%20it%20when%20I%20quit%20my%20job%20and%20use%20the%20money%20to%20road%20trip%20around%20the%20U.S.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20just%20never%20quite%20understood%20the%20point%20of%20letting%20my%20money%20sit%20around%20in%20someone%20else's%20pocket%20for%20decades%20until%2C%20hopefully%2C%20I%20could%20one%20day%20spend%20it%20%E2%80%94%20not%20when%20there%20were%20so%20many%20things%20I%20could%20spend%20it%20on%20now.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThen%20I%20watched%20my%20Dad%20retire%20at%20least%20a%20decade%20before%20many%20of%20his%20peers%2C%20and%20my%20entire%20perspective%20changed.%20My%20stepmom%20retired%20even%20younger%20after%20my%20Dad%20convinced%20her%20to%20join%20him%20in%20his%20plan%20for%20early%20retirement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHoping%20it%20wasn't%20too%20late%20for%20me%20to%20get%20my%20finances%20on%20track%2C%20I%20asked%20them%20how%20they%20did%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EHow%20my%20parents%20retired%20early%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20Dad%20had%20always%20planned%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Ffinancial-independence-retire-early%5C%22%3Eretire%20early%3C%2Fa%3E.%20He%20was%20frugal%20and%20highly%20practical%20growing%20up%E2%81%A0%20%E2%80%94%20my%20sister%20and%20I%20ate%20a%20lot%20of%20%240.50%20frozen%20pot%20pies%20and%20didn't%20get%20new%20sneakers%20until%20there%20were%20holes%20in%20our%20current%20ones.%20He%20was%20generous%20with%20stuff%20that%20mattered%2C%20though%2C%20like%20educational%20opportunities%20that%20could%20set%20us%20up%20for%20a%20better%20future.%20But%20education%20is%20an%20investment%3B%20shoes%20are%20not.%20He%20understood%20that%20money%20invested%20usually%20provides%20more%20value%20to%20your%20life%2C%20in%20the%20long%20run%2C%20than%20money%20spent.%20You%20invest%20first%2C%20then%20you%20spend.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20stepmom%2C%20on%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20never%20had%20plans%20to%20retire%20early%20until%20she%20started%20dating%20my%20Dad.%20When%20he%20told%20her%20he%20wanted%20to%20retire%20by%2050%2C%20she%20looked%20at%20him%20incredulously.%20%26quot%3BI%20told%20him%2C%20there's%20no%20freaking%20way%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20recalled%20to%20me.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShe%20played%20along%20anyway.%20As%20it%20turns%20out%2C%20his%20goal%20wasn't%20so%20unrealistic.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20Dad%20would%20have%20been%20on%20track%20to%20retire%20by%2050%2C%20which%20was%20a%20stretch%20goal%2C%20if%20it%20weren't%20for%20the%202008%20recession%2C%20which%20decimated%20his%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-retirement-plans%5C%22%3Eretirement%20accounts%3C%2Fa%3E.%20However%2C%20he%20was%20able%20to%20eventually%20recover%20and%20retire%20at%2055.%20My%20stepmom%20retired%20at%2049.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBoth%20my%20Dad%20and%20stepmom%20worked%20in%20sales%20and%20marketing%20for%20a%20high-tech%20company%20by%20way%20of%20degrees%20in%20electrical%20engineering%2C%20so%20it's%20worth%20stating%20up%20front%20that%20they%20both%20earned%20salaries%20that%20most%20would%20consider%20more%20than%20comfortable.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERegardless%2C%20most%20people%20%E2%80%94%20my%20non-engineer%20self%20included%20%E2%80%94%20can%20apply%20the%20advice%20they%20gave%20me.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E1.%20Set%20a%20goal%2C%20create%20a%20budget%2C%20and%20track%20your%20progress%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ESetting%20clear%20goals%20and%20tracking%20your%20progress%20will%20make%20all%20the%20difference.%20It%20wasn't%20until%20my%20stepmom%20checked%20in%20on%20their%20progress%20and%20saw%20their%20money%20growing%20according%20to%20plan%20that%20she%20believed%20they%20could%20retire%20early.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20realized%20it%20was%20real%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20told%20me.%20%26quot%3BWhen%20you%20make%20saving%20a%20priority%2C%20retirement%20becomes%20possible.%20Money%20makes%20more%20money%2C%20and%20it%20makes%20it%20surprisingly%20quick.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20first%20thing%20they%20did%20was%20figure%20out%20exactly%20how%20much%20money%20they'd%20need%20to%20comfortably%20retire%20when%20my%20dad%20hit%2050%20and%20live%20off%20that%20money%20well%20into%20their%2090s.%20Their%20retirement%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-budgeting-apps%5C%22%3Ebudget%3C%2Fa%3E%20included%20a%20salary%20equal%20to%20their%20pre-retirement%20pay%20and%20line-item%20expenses%20for%20things%20like%20healthcare.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20creating%20a%20retirement%20budget%2C%20they%20worked%20backward%20to%20figure%20out%20how%20much%20money%20they'd%20need%20to%20save%20each%20year%20to%20get%20there%20by%20age%2050%2C%20taking%20into%20account%20the%20expected%20rate%20of%20return%20on%20their%20investments.%20Then%2C%20they%20cut%20spending%20and%20invested%20all%20their%20extra%20earnings%20to%20meet%20that%20goal.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThey%20regularly%20checked%20in%20with%20their%20budget%20and%20did%20a%20full%20progress%20assessment%20every%20six%20months.%20Eventually%2C%20they%20started%20meeting%20with%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fbest-online-financial-advisors%5C%22%3Efinancial%20advisor%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20these%20biannual%20check-ins%2C%20and%20they've%20continued%20them%20in%20retirement%20to%20ensure%20they're%20still%20where%20they%20need%20to%20be.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E2.%20Avoid%20lifestyle%20inflation%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELifestyle%20inflation%2C%20or%20increasing%20your%20cost%20of%20living%20every%20time%20your%20income%20increases%2C%20is%20one%20of%20the%20most%20insidious%20ways%20to%20destroy%20a%20retirement%20plan.%20It%20often%20lands%20folks%20in%20debt.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20my%20parents%2C%20living%20below%20their%20means%20was%20essential%20to%20retiring%20early.%20They%20invested%20at%20least%20half%20of%20any%20raise.%20My%20Dad's%20bonuses%20at%20work%20were%20invested%20in%20rental%20properties%20that%20could%20generate%20income.%20When%20they%20got%20married%2C%20my%20parents%20bought%20a%20house%20that%20was%20priced%20at%20half%20of%20what%20they%20could%20actually%20afford.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThey%20also%20didn't%20go%20overboard%20on%20cars.%20Our%20whole%20family%20has%20always%20driven%20Hondas%2C%20and%20my%20parents%20drive%20a%20car%20until%20it%20stops%20running.%20They%20did%20get%20all%20of%20us%20kids%20cars%2C%20but%20we%20got%20old%2C%20used%20cars%20for%20a%20couple%20grand%20%E2%80%94%20mine%20was%20a%201990%20Acura%20Integra%20%E2%80%94%20and%20paid%20for%20them%20in%20cash.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E3.%20Invest%20aggressively%20...%20and%20diversify%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELike%20most%20people%2C%20a%20401(k)%20was%20central%20to%20my%20parents'%20retirement%20plan.%20They%20took%20full%20advantage%20of%20employer%20matching%20from%20the%20start%20and%20worked%20up%20to%20maxing%20their%20401(k)s%20as%20early%20as%20possible.%20My%20stepmom%20also%20runs%20a%20consulting%20business%2C%20so%20she%20opened%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fsep-ira%5C%22%3ESEP-IRA%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20is%20an%20option%20for%20folks%20who%20are%20self-employed.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBecause%20they%20wanted%20to%20retire%20early%2C%20my%20parents%20had%20to%20have%20other%20investments%20they%20could%20rely%20on%20for%20retirement%20income.%20Retirement%20accounts%2C%20like%20a%20401(k)%20or%20SEP%20IRA%2C%20shouldn't%20be%20touched%20until%20you've%20actually%20reached%20retirement%20age%20(59%20%C2%BD).%20If%20you%20withdraw%20funds%20early%2C%20you'll%20incur%20a%20hefty%20penalty.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESo%2C%20my%20parents%20also%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fhow-to-invest-in-stocks%5C%22%3Einvested%20in%20stocks%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20bonds%2C%20and%20rental%20properties%20to%20provide%20income%20until%20they%20turn%2059%20%C2%BD.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20the%20recession%2C%20my%20parents%20bought%20foreclosed%20houses%20in%20cash%20at%20extremely%20low%20prices.%20They%20renovated%20the%20houses%2C%20doing%20all%20the%20work%20themselves%20to%20save%20money%2C%20and%20then%20rented%20them%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20properties%20now%20serve%20as%20income%20generators%20for%20the%20early%20years%20of%20their%20retirement%20as%20well%20as%20a%20safety%20net%2C%20as%20they%20can%20be%20sold%20off%20one%20by%20one.%20My%20parents%20know%20that%20they%20could%20weather%20a%2030%25%20cut%20on%20what%20they%20live%20off%20of%2C%20thanks%20to%20the%20properties%2C%20and%20still%20be%20fine.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20addition%20to%20rental%20income%2C%20they've%20set%20up%20a%20bond%20ladder%20to%20live%20off%20of%20in%20the%20short-term.%20Each%20year%20for%20the%20next%20four%20or%20five%20years%2C%20they%20have%20bonds%20maturing%20that%20provide%20them%20with%20income.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E4.%20Consider%20a%20part-time%20backup%20plan%20for%20income%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20stepmom%20is%20younger%20than%20my%20Dad%20and%20planned%20to%20work%20a%20little%20longer.%20However%2C%20rather%20than%20continue%20with%20the%20company%20where%20they'd%20both%20worked%2C%20she%20decided%20to%20start%20her%20own%20consulting%20business%20online%20that%20would%20help%20her%20transition%20to%20full-time%20retirement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20stepmom%20still%20does%20consulting%20work%20on%20the%20side%20for%20%26quot%3Bfun%20money.%26quot%3B%20They've%20used%20this%20consulting%20income%20to%20go%20on%20a%20safari%20in%20South%20Africa%2C%20take%20their%20parents%20to%20Germany%2C%20and%20throw%20a%20big%20anniversary%20celebration%20with%20the%20whole%20family%20in%20St.%20Thomas%2C%20where%20they%20now%20live%20part%20of%20the%20year.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIf%20anything%20ever%20happened%20to%20one%20of%20their%20income%20sources%2C%20they%20could%20always%20lean%20on%20my%20stepmom's%20consulting.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWhy%20early%20retirement%20was%20important%20to%20my%20parents%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EA%20lot%20of%20people%20my%20age%20(20s%20and%20early%2030s)%20can't%20envision%20retiring%20at%20all%2C%20let%20alone%20early%2C%20so%20it%20surprised%20me%20that%20my%20Dad%20had%20been%20planning%20early%20retirement%20since%20he%20was%20my%20age.%20I%20asked%20if%20any%20life%20experiences%20or%20lessons%20had%20helped%20him%20gain%20that%20foresight%20at%20such%20a%20young%20age.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20think%20it%20was%20your%20Dad's%20mom%20dying%20young%20and%20Alzheimer's%20running%20in%20the%20family%2C%26quot%3B%20my%20stepmom%20offered.%20%26quot%3BHe%20felt%20like%20he%20really%20wanted%2C%20while%20he%20was%20in%20good%20health%2C%20to%20have%20his%20own%20life.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20Dad%20agreed.%20%26quot%3BThat%20was%20part%20of%20it%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%20He%20also%20brought%20up%20my%20aunt%2C%20his%20sister%2C%20who%20died%20of%20cancer.%20When%20he%20saw%20how%20quickly%20she%20went%20from%20perfectly%20healthy%20to%20very%20sick%2C%20they%20doubled%20down%20on%20their%20plan%20to%20retire.%20%26quot%3BI%20could've%20kept%20working%2C%20but%20when%20your%20aunt%20passed%20within%20six%20months%20of%20being%20diagnosed%20I%20said%2C%20'Why%20are%20we%20waiting%3F'%20I%20just%20wanted%20the%20freedom%20to%20do%20what%20we%20wanted%20when%20we%20wanted.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe%20enjoyed%20%5Bour%20work%5D%2C%20but%20it%20was%20like%2C%20this%20isn't%20what%20I%20am%2C%26quot%3B%20my%20stepmom%20added.%20%26quot%3BThis%20isn't%20what%20I%20want%20my%20whole%20life%20to%20be.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ENow%2C%20they%20spend%20almost%20half%20the%20year%20in%20the%20Caribbean%2C%20learning%20to%20play%20guitar%2C%20going%20on%20sailing%20trips%2C%20and%20doing%20volunteer%20work.%20They've%20traveled%20all%20over%20the%20globe%2C%20spending%20several%20months%20road-tripping%20to%20the%20best%20U.S.%20national%20parks%2C%20exploring%20Europe%2C%20spotting%20wildlife%20in%20South%20Africa%2C%20cruising%20the%20Panama%20Canal%2C%20and%20visiting%20relatives.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWatching%20them%2C%20I've%20learned%20that%20saving%20money%20is%20the%20opposite%20of%20letting%20it%20sit%20around%20collecting%20dust.%20If%20invested%20properly%2C%20that%20money%20grows%20indefinitely%2C%20and%20it%20will%20probably%20